    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-09-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-09-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="572"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d572">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">235.11 B 76/93</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Paraguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dickson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Asunción</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-09-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 23, 1921</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received October 26.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 890</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acquaint you with reference
                    to my despatch No. 864 of August 29th<note n="8" xml:id="d572fn8">Not
                        printed.</note> and of a conversation I have had with the Sub-Secretary of
                    the Foreign Office, Señor E. Egusquiza, at which time we viewed the original
                    treaty of extradition between the United States and Paraguay and expressed our
                    opinion respecting Article II paragraph 19, as published in the pamphlet series
                    No. 584.</p>
                <p>The question of interpretation of paragraph 19 from Spanish into English is not
                    exactly the same but as the original treaty signed by Nicolay A. Grevstad and
                    Doctor Eusebio Ayala is in both English and Spanish the Paraguayan Government
                    withold [<hi rend="italic">will hold?</hi>], according to Mr. Egusquiza’s
                    interpretation of the matter, that False Testimony is the same as Perjury
                    according to the English version of the definition of Perjury.</p>
                <p>Mr. Egusquiza also pointed out that Doctor Eusebio Ayala, the Paraguayan
                    signatory of the treaty was sufficiently well versed in the English language to
                    be certain of the exact meaning thereof.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Samuel S. Dickson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
